Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Bring a #medium saucepan{} of water to the boil with
@salt{1/2%tsp}. Peel the @potatoes{450%g} and chop into 2cm chunks. Trim the root
and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways then thinly slice
widthways. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly
chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped). Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g}.
Chop the @cod fillets{2} into 2cm chunks.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Once boiling, add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a
knife through, ~{15-20%minutes}. Meanwhile, pop a #large frying pan{} on medium-high
heat. Add a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} and half the @unsalted butter{15%g}. Allow the
butter to melt, then add the leek. Stir-fry until the leek is soft, ~{3-4%minutes},
then stir in the @plain flour{24%g}. Cook, stirring constantly, until it forms a
paste consistency, ~{1-2%minutes}. Gradually add the @water{150%ml}, stirring
constantly, then add the @vegetable stock paste{10%g}. Bring to the boil, stirring
continuously then reduce the heat and simmer, stirring, until the mixture thickens
and is smooth and creamy, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @creme fraiche{150%g}, parsley and the fish, stir, and cook for ~{3-4%minutes}.
Taste the sauce and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if necessary. Add the
@king prawns{150%g} to the mix, cook for ~{2-3%minutes}. The prawns should be
par-cooked at this point.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when it is opaque in the middle.

Pour into an appropriately-sized #ovenproof dish{}.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan off the
heat. Add the remaining @unsalted butter{15%g} and a splash of @?milk{splash} and
mash until smooth using a #potato masher{}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.
Spoon the mash on top of the fish mixture and spread it out evenly. Sprinkle over
the grated cheese and bake on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> TIP: Pop the dish on a #baking tray{} to catch any drips as it bakes.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Wash out your (now empty) #frying pan{}. Trim the @green beans{150%g}. Heat a drizzle
of @oil{drizzle} in your frying pan on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add
the beans and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Stir-fry until starting to
char, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and add a splash of @water{?splash}. Cover
the pan with a #lid{} or some foil and cook until tender, ~{2-3%minutes}. Then remove
the pan from the heat.

Spoon the fish pie into #bowls{} or onto #plates{} and serve with the green beans on
the side. Enjoy!